@model function m14_1(cafe, afternoon, wait)
    a ~ Normal(5, 2)
    b ~ Normal(-1, 0.5)
    _cafe ~ filldist(Exponential(), 2)
    Rho ~ LKJ(2, 2)
    # build sigma matrix manually, to avoid numerical errors
#     (, ) = _cafe
#     sc = [[^2, *] [*, ^2]]
#      = Rho .* sc
    # the same as above, but shorter and generic
     = (_cafe .* _cafe') .* Rho
    ab ~ filldist(MvNormal([a,b], ), N_cafes)
    a = ab[1,cafe]
    b = ab[2,cafe]
     = @. a + b * afternoon
     ~ Exponential()
    for i  eachindex(wait)
        wait[i] ~ Normal([i], )
    end
end

Random.seed!(1)

m14_1_df = DataFrame(m14_1_ch);

In [19]:
d = DataFrame(CSV.File("data/chimpanzees.csv", delim=';'));
d.treatment = 1 .+ d.prosoc_left .+ 2*d.condition;
d.block_id = d.block;

Random.seed!(123)

@model function m14_2(L, tid, actor, block_id)
    tid_len = length(levels(tid))
    act_len = length(levels(actor))
    blk_len = length(levels(block_id))
    g ~ filldist(Normal(), tid_len)

    _actor ~ filldist(Exponential(), tid_len)
    _actor ~ LKJ(tid_len, 2)
    _actor = (_actor .* _actor') .* _actor
    alpha ~ filldist(MvNormal(zeros(tid_len), _actor), act_len)

    _block ~ filldist(Exponential(), tid_len)
    _block ~ LKJ(tid_len, 2)
    _block = (_block .* _block') .* _block
    beta ~ filldist(MvNormal(zeros(tid_len), _block), blk_len)
    
    for i  eachindex(L)
        p = logistic(g[tid[i]] + alpha[tid[i], actor[i]] + beta[tid[i], block_id[i]])
        L[i] ~ Bernoulli(p)
    end
end


m14_2_ch = sample(m14_2(d.pulled_left, d.treatment, d.actor, d.block_id), HMC(0.01, 10), 1000);
m14_2_df = DataFrame(m14_2_ch);

@model function m14_3(L, tid, actor, block_id)
    tid_len = length(levels(tid))
    act_len = length(levels(actor))
    blk_len = length(levels(block_id))
    g ~ filldist(Normal(), tid_len)

    _actor ~ filldist(Exponential(), tid_len)
    # LKJCholesky is not usable in Turing: https://github.com/TuringLang/Turing.jl/issues/1629
    _actor ~ LKJ(tid_len, 2)    
    _actor_L = cholesky(Symmetric(_actor)).L
    z_actor ~ filldist(MvNormal(zeros(tid_len), 1), act_len)
    alpha = (_actor .* _actor_L) * z_actor

    _block ~ filldist(Exponential(), tid_len)
    _block ~ LKJ(tid_len, 2)
    _block_L = cholesky(Symmetric(_block)).L        
    z_block ~ filldist(MvNormal(zeros(tid_len), 1), blk_len)
    beta = (_block .* _block_L) * z_block

    for i  eachindex(L)
        p = logistic(g[tid[i]] + alpha[tid[i], actor[i]] + beta[tid[i], block_id[i]])
        L[i] ~ Bernoulli(p)
    end
end

# Hm, this is less stable and slower than m14_2...
# So if you know how to improve it - PR or open the issue in the repo

l_fun = (r, (ai, ti)) -> begin
    bi = 5
    g = get(r, "g[$ti]", missing)
    
    _actor = get(r, "_actor[$ti]", missing)
    _actor = reshape(collect(r[r"_actor"]), (4, 4))
    _actor_L = cholesky(Symmetric(_actor)).L
    z_actor = reshape(collect(r[r"z_actor"]), (4, 7))
    alpha = (_actor .* _actor_L) * z_actor
    a = alpha[ti, ai]
    
    _block = get(r, "_block[$ti]", missing)
    _block = reshape(collect(r[r"_block"]), (4, 4))
    _block_L = cholesky(Symmetric(_block)).L
    z_block = reshape(collect(r[r"z_block"]), (4, 6))
    beta = (_block .* _block_L) * z_block
    b = beta[ti, bi]
    
    logistic(g + a + b)
end

@model function m14_6(W, E, Q, WE)
     ~ filldist(Exponential(), 2)
     ~ LKJ(2, 2)
    aW ~ Normal(0, 0.2)
    aE ~ Normal(0, 0.2)
    bEW ~ Normal(0, 0.5)
    bQE ~ Normal(0, 0.5)
    W = @. aW + bEW*E
    E = @. aW + bQE*Q
     = ( .* ') .* 
    for i  eachindex(WE)
        WE[i] ~ MvNormal([W[i], E[i]], )
    end
end

kl_data = (
    N = nrow(kl_dyads), 
    N_households = maximum(kl_dyads.hidB),
    did = kl_dyads.did,
    hidA = kl_dyads.hidA,
    hidB = kl_dyads.hidB,
    giftsAB = kl_dyads.giftsAB,
    giftsBA = kl_dyads.giftsBA,
)

@model function m14_7(N, N_households, hidA, hidB, did, giftsAB, giftsBA)
    a ~ Normal()
    _gr ~ LKJ(2, 4)
    _gr ~ filldist(Exponential(), 2)
     = (_gr .* _gr') .* _gr
    gr ~ filldist(MvNormal(), N_households)
    
    # dyad effects (use 2 z values)
    z ~ filldist(Normal(), N)
    z ~ filldist(Normal(), N)
    z = [z z]'
    _d ~ Exponential()
    _d ~ LKJ(2, 8)
    L__d = cholesky(Symmetric(_d)).L
    d = (_d .* L__d) * z

    _AB = exp.(a .+ gr[1, hidA] .+ gr[2, hidB] .+ d[1, did])
    _BA = exp.(a .+ gr[1, hidB] .+ gr[2, hidA] .+ d[2, did])
    for i  eachindex(giftsAB)
        giftsAB[i] ~ Poisson(_AB[i])
        giftsBA[i] ~ Poisson(_BA[i])
    end
    return d
end

model = m14_7(
    kl_data.N, kl_data.N_households, kl_data.hidA, kl_data.hidB, 
    kl_data.did, kl_data.giftsAB, kl_data.giftsBA
)
m14_7_ch = sample(model, 
    NUTS(1000, 0.65, init_=0.025), 
    1000)
m14_7_df = DataFrame(m14_7_ch);

Code 14.39

Adapted from example here: https://discourse.julialang.org/t/gaussian-process-model-with-turing/42453

In [46]:
d = DataFrame(CSV.File("data/Kline2.csv"))
d[:, "society"] = 1:10;

dat_list = (
    T = d.total_tools,
    P = d.population,
    society = d.society,
    Dmat = Matrix(islandsDistMatrix),
)

@model function m14_8(T, P, society, Dmat)
     ~ Exponential(2)
     ~ Exponential(0.5)
    a ~ Exponential()
    b ~ Exponential()
    g ~ Exponential()
    
     =  * exp.(- * Dmat^2) + LinearAlgebra.I * (0.01 + )
    k ~ MvNormal(zeros(10), )
     = @. (a*P^b/g)*exp(k[society])
    @. T ~ Poisson()
end

Random.seed!(1)
m14_8_ch = sample(m14_8(dat_list.T, dat_list.P, dat_list.society, dat_list.Dmat), 
    NUTS(), 1000)
m14_8_df = DataFrame(m14_8_ch);
